WEBVTT

00:28.738 --> 00:29.619
Big Hills Church.

00:29.900 --> 00:36.489
My name is Whitney Wiseman and I am so glad to be with you all whether you are joining us online or you are here in the room.

00:36.509 --> 00:38.211
We are glad that you are here.

00:38.231 --> 00:41.576
We are grateful for the opportunity to gather together.

00:41.596 --> 00:44.881
It is a great Sunday in Austin.

00:45.501 --> 00:48.446
In fact, I can think of about 49 reasons.

00:48.726 --> 00:51.209
It is a good day to be in Austin today.

00:51.270 --> 00:57.298
But wherever you are, we're glad that you are here and joining with us.

00:57.634 --> 01:04.175
If we haven't met before, my name is Whitney, and I have been on staff here at Lakeville Church for 13 years.

01:05.238 --> 01:09.010
I am currently the Director of Spiritual Development, which

01:09.090 --> 01:11.734
Basically means I hope people connect and grow.

01:11.754 --> 01:26.615
So if you are looking to connect into the life of Lake Hills Church, if you're looking to take your next step in your relationship with Christ, stop by the hub or scan the QR card and see back in front of you because we would love to help you do that.

01:27.156 --> 01:28.818
That was just a shameless plug.

01:28.898 --> 01:33.303
We, my husband and I, my husband serves at Lake Hill Church.

01:33.323 --> 01:35.125
He plays the keyboard a lot of Sundays.

01:35.165 --> 01:36.346
You might recognize him.

01:36.366 --> 01:39.229
He's not here today because he's playing at ACL this afternoon.

01:39.289 --> 01:41.171
So big weekend for the wise men's.

01:42.172 --> 01:48.879
We have a two-year-old and a four-year-old and we are so grateful to be a part of this church family.

01:49.720 --> 01:55.727
Over the last 13 years, I have served in different areas and different ministries on our staff.

01:56.167 --> 01:58.770
And in 2011,

01:58.882 --> 02:03.327
I was working as an intern with our student ministry.

02:04.008 --> 02:10.556
I was serving alongside then Kaylee Wilson, who is now Kaylee McDaniel.

02:10.636 --> 02:13.599
She and her husband Jordan oversee all of our next in ministry.

02:13.639 --> 02:15.862
So give a shout out to Kaylee and Jordan.

02:15.962 --> 02:19.286
If you have kids or students, they are killing it.

02:20.127 --> 02:22.770
But way before Jordan, it was me and Kaylee.

02:23.330 --> 02:32.641
And we were wrapping up a really great week of camp and we found ourselves in a cabin with a group of sixth grade girls.

02:33.522 --> 02:42.894
It was at the end of the week and we were kind of talking about our takeaways and recapping the highlights, the fun things, the things that we've learned and we were going around the circle.

02:44.075 --> 02:49.682
And there's a precious sixth grade girl with all the confidence in the world tells us.

02:50.818 --> 03:04.532
I have learned a lot about God this week, but one of my main takeaways is that now I definitely know that God is an old man with a beard.

03:06.116 --> 03:08.562
And Kaylee and I just looked at each other

03:09.218 --> 03:10.601
very confused.

03:10.821 --> 03:17.493
I am still perplexed at how she came to this very confident conclusion that God is an old man with a beard.

03:17.533 --> 03:22.402
But I love that she had this image of God in her mind because we all do.

03:22.442 --> 03:26.610
We all have these images of who God is.

03:27.074 --> 03:27.715
in our minds.

03:27.775 --> 03:30.439
And a lot of times those come directly from Scripture.

03:30.479 --> 03:38.530
God through Scripture gives us images and word pictures and metaphors to describe God and the kingdom of God.

03:38.811 --> 03:49.746
And one of the primary ways that God describes the kingdom of God, the family of faith is a family, which is why we kicked off a sermon series last week called

03:49.858 --> 04:04.876
family style where we are exploring the interconnected facets of the family and how God communicates God's grace and the gospel through those of various dynamics and aspects of family.

04:05.997 --> 04:11.804
We talked last week about the value of family and about family values.

04:12.185 --> 04:19.794
We looked at Joshua who was bringing his family, who's bringing the people of God into the land that God had promised them.

04:20.482 --> 04:27.691
And as he settles his family, he boldly stated, as for me and my house, we will serve the Lord.

04:28.211 --> 04:39.004
He named and exemplified what and who he would stand for in this new season and this new place and this new start for him and his family, for God's people.

04:40.546 --> 04:45.132
I love that in scripture, we are identified as a family of faith.

04:45.172 --> 04:50.418
And I love being a part of this family of faith in particular.

04:50.498 --> 04:53.183
I don't mean to brag, but we got a pretty good one.

04:53.964 --> 04:55.687
Turn your name around and tell them we got a good one.

04:57.230 --> 04:58.833
We have a great family.

04:59.253 --> 05:01.678
I have personally benefited from this family.

05:01.898 --> 05:04.883
You guys dropped off meals when our babies were born.

05:04.984 --> 05:08.570
You have texted when we were sick, checking in on us.

05:08.850 --> 05:15.442
The ladies in my Bible study prayed for months and months and months and months.

05:15.522 --> 05:16.945
that our kids would sleep through the night.

05:17.246 --> 05:25.423
You guys have showed up and checked on us in some of our lowest moments and you have shared in the joy of some of our best moments.

05:26.406 --> 05:34.002
I know that I'm not the only one who has benefited from this family of faith because I have seen you guys show up for each other over and over again.

05:34.210 --> 05:37.195
You guys have shown up at the site of an accident.

05:37.295 --> 05:39.579
You have visited each other in the hospital.

05:39.920 --> 05:46.932
I've seen you change flat tires in the parking lot or jumped each other's cars, cared for each other's kids on the playground.

05:47.593 --> 05:55.266
I've seen a few of you respectfully disagree about some things, but all the while we have kept the gospel the number one thing.

05:55.907 --> 05:59.794
Now we're not perfect, but we are family.

06:00.802 --> 06:10.918
One of the Bible's central metaphors for God is that of God as a parent, we talk a lot about God the Father and us as God's children.

06:10.958 --> 06:16.247
But scripture gives us metaphors, gives us images of both God as Father and as Mother.

06:16.267 --> 06:26.223
1 John 3 1 says, see what love the Father has given us that we should be called children of God.

06:26.283 --> 06:28.306
And that is what we are.

06:29.410 --> 06:36.401
Isaiah 49, 15 says, can a woman forget her nursing child or show no compassion for the child of her womb?

06:37.122 --> 06:41.428
Even these might forget, yet I will not forget you.

06:42.830 --> 06:53.106
These verses give us a picture of God as a parent who cares, who is compassionate, who is giving, who is a vulnerable, and who is relational.

06:53.666 --> 07:14.938
God as a parent is one of many biblical metaphors, one of many images that God gives us, but it's a familiar lens for each of us through which we can see God and a familiar framework for which we can engage with God because as Pastor Mac reminded us last week, for better or for worse, everybody's got family.

07:16.240 --> 07:23.090
Now while everybody does have family, I want to take a moment to acknowledge that we might not all be parents in this room,

07:23.394 --> 07:30.962
Perhaps you are longing to be a parent or you have lost a parent or you are in a strained relationship with a parent or a child.

07:31.042 --> 07:38.571
And so if you have some mixed feelings about this idea, this image of God as a parent, you are not alone.

07:39.672 --> 07:41.774
We see you and we love you.

07:42.075 --> 07:46.139
And more importantly, God sees you and God loves you.

07:46.419 --> 07:51.265
God's love knows no bounds, in fact, and the character of God.

07:51.625 --> 07:52.466
For those of us,

07:52.642 --> 07:55.105
who are parents, this is a great reminder.

07:55.966 --> 08:04.815
But it doesn't matter where you are, because this pattern of parental love informs how we engage with all people at every level.

08:06.097 --> 08:18.130
First, God's parental love is shown for us as God engages with us, as God teaches, God disciplines, God develops, God guides,

08:18.786 --> 08:21.149
and responds to our needs.

08:21.469 --> 08:39.390
Deuteronomy 32 verses 11 and 12 says, as an eagle stirs up its nest and hovers over its young, as it spreads its wings and takes them up and bears them aloft on its pinions, the Lord alone guided him in reference to Jacob and the people of Israel.

08:39.811 --> 08:46.098
Here we see a parent who is engaged, a parent who directs and protects with boldness and with courage,

08:46.274 --> 08:50.340
God who responds to our needs.

08:51.061 --> 08:55.729
God is not a great clockmaker who winds up the clock and sets it on his shelf.

08:56.029 --> 08:59.795
Not a God who created the world and set it in emotion and watches from afar.

09:00.096 --> 09:09.330
No, we have a God who is engaged with us in our very midst, who sees us and knows us and responds to our needs.

09:09.762 --> 09:17.893
Oh, God's parental love for us desires, our well-being, asking for our obedience to God's will and God's ways.

09:18.273 --> 09:26.645
Hebrews 9, verse, Hebrews 12, 9 through 11 says, Moreover, we had human parents to discipline us and we respected them.

09:27.586 --> 09:34.996
Should we not even more, should we not be even more willing to be subject to the father of spirits and live?

09:35.877 --> 09:39.602
For they disciplined us for a short time as it seemed best to them.

09:40.226 --> 09:45.916
But he disciplines us for good in order that we may share in his holiness.

09:46.978 --> 09:57.618
Now, discipline always seems painful rather than pleasant at the time, but later it yields the peaceful fruit of righteousness to those who have been trained by it.

09:57.922 --> 10:13.305
You see, God desires and demands our obedience for our well-being so that we might produce fruits of peacefulness, of righteousness, so that we might reflect God's holiness to be the people that God intended us to be.

10:13.345 --> 10:16.770
There have always been natural consequences.

10:16.830 --> 10:21.016
From the very beginning, we see Adam and Eve had to be expelled from the garden.

10:21.076 --> 10:27.826
We see Moses, who wasn't allowed to enter the promised land because of his disobedience.

10:28.130 --> 10:36.249
We see Israel who was subject to exile, to foreign land, and under foreign rule.

10:37.312 --> 10:39.156
But this is so important.

10:39.697 --> 10:45.010
God's motive, God's directive action is always

10:45.250 --> 10:47.433
out of God's love for us.

10:47.774 --> 10:54.664
This love realizes that we are our best self when we submit ourselves to God's will and God's ways.

10:55.005 --> 10:56.527
This love is not conditional.

10:56.607 --> 10:58.470
It is not based on our behavior.

10:58.510 --> 11:03.558
Rather, it is fully exemplified in Christ and this love indoors forever.

11:03.598 --> 11:11.730
This love meets us where we are and engages with us, responds to our needs.

11:12.226 --> 11:19.035
It does not abandon us to the consequences of sin, but it responds with grace in our greatest moment of need.

11:19.776 --> 11:23.962
We see that again throughout Scripture, the rainbow and the covenant after the flood.

11:24.463 --> 11:28.969
We see how God liberated Israel who were slaves in Egypt.

11:29.830 --> 11:33.776
We see God's rescue of Israel from Babylonian exile.

11:33.796 --> 11:41.266
And ultimately, we experience that ourselves when we receive salvation from our sins through Christ.

11:41.602 --> 11:49.171
God's responsive and engaging love for us is evident and apparent throughout Scripture and in our very lives today.

11:50.413 --> 11:55.719
Second, God's love shows us just how much God cares for us.

11:56.360 --> 12:08.995
Isaiah 66, 12 and 13 says, and you shall nurse and be carried on her arm and bounced on her knee as a mother comforts her child, so I will comfort you.

12:09.556 --> 12:11.538
You shall be comforted in Jerusalem.

12:12.546 --> 12:20.699
First Peter 5'7 says, cast all your anxieties on him because he cares for you.

12:21.520 --> 12:25.366
In the midst of our suffering and in our times of need, God cares for us.

12:25.426 --> 12:27.229
God is concerned about us.

12:27.730 --> 12:35.442
The beginning of Exodus says that Israel cried out to God and God heard their cries and remembered his people.

12:36.386 --> 12:41.933
when Hagar was expelled, ran away from Abram and Sarah's home.

12:42.333 --> 12:54.508
She encounters God and the wilderness, and she identifies him as a God who sees throughout scripture God as described as a shepherd who cares, who nurtures for his sheep.

12:55.049 --> 12:59.594
Jesus doesn't come in like a superhero and sweeps away all the bad.

13:00.155 --> 13:01.717
No, he comes first.

13:02.258 --> 13:03.900
He enters into our humanity.

13:03.940 --> 13:05.842
He takes on our flesh,

13:06.082 --> 13:16.336
so that he may know our pain and suffering, so that he can stand with us, so he might sit next to us in our pain and know what we are feeling.

13:16.456 --> 13:23.625
And then through the cross and the resurrection offers us comfort and hope and peace and the fullness of salvation's victory.

13:23.926 --> 13:27.571
The caring nature of God is revealed through the death and resurrection.

13:27.851 --> 13:32.978
The empty tomb is a demonstration of God's costly care for us.

13:33.954 --> 13:37.538
God cares about us intimately and individually.

13:38.219 --> 13:41.643
In Luke 15, God is described as a shepherd who leaves the 99.

13:41.743 --> 13:44.006
We're just saying a song about that, that last song.

13:44.026 --> 13:47.170
He leaves the 99 to go after the one.

13:47.971 --> 13:59.505
Luke 15 also describes God as a woman who loses a coin and sweeps her whole house for it because she recognizes the value and cares that much about the one lost coin.

14:00.266 --> 14:03.570
There are very few things in life that I care that much about.

14:04.834 --> 14:08.337
When I lose things, they're just gone forever.

14:09.138 --> 14:15.284
Either that or they will find me, but there's just very little chance that I am going to find them.

14:15.304 --> 14:18.307
My husband, on the other hand, he cares a lot about everything.

14:18.868 --> 14:28.897
And so when things are lost, he must find them, which is very inconvenient when something is lost before bed, because no one's sleeping until this lost thing is found.

14:29.298 --> 14:32.561
But it's very convenient when I lose my car keys.

14:32.821 --> 14:33.842
We don't have to buy a new car.

14:34.370 --> 14:36.192
And it goes up to me like, well, car keys are gone.

14:36.453 --> 14:37.054
Gotta buy a new car.

14:38.195 --> 14:39.617
My husband like finds them.

14:40.558 --> 14:43.823
That is just a small image of how much God cares for us, right?

14:43.963 --> 14:52.855
That God would leave the 99 to go after the one, to search for each one of us, the woman who searches the whole house for the coin to bring it back.

14:54.477 --> 14:56.840
God also gives generously to us.

14:56.940 --> 15:01.266
That parental love is demonstrated in God's generosity to us.

15:01.890 --> 15:10.524
John 3 16 says that God so loved the world that He gave His only Son, that whoever believes in Him may not perish but have eternal life.

15:10.825 --> 15:18.878
So not only does God give of God's very self, God sends the Son Jesus to us so that God might give us eternal life.

15:19.479 --> 15:24.467
And if that wasn't enough, when we step into our relationship with Christ, we are given the Holy Spirit.

15:24.868 --> 15:26.130
Acts 1 8 says,

15:26.498 --> 15:31.045
that you will receive power when the Spirit comes upon you and you will be my witnesses.

15:31.425 --> 15:37.234
Roman tells us that the same power that raised Jesus from the dead is in us.

15:38.055 --> 15:40.079
That never ceases to blow my mind.

15:40.119 --> 15:41.200
That God cares about us.

15:41.381 --> 15:54.040
That God is generous enough to give of God's very self to guide us, to help us, to give us comfort and peace and ultimately to give us grace.

15:54.060 --> 15:55.602
In the beginning in the garden,

15:55.874 --> 15:58.418
Adam and Eve walked hand in hand with God.

15:59.239 --> 16:04.346
This was the most intimate relationship, much like a parent and a newborn child.

16:05.267 --> 16:08.612
The Adam and Eve were fully known and unashamed.

16:08.652 --> 16:11.856
They were fully nurtured and fully dependent on God.

16:12.497 --> 16:16.703
But then Adam and Eve, much like a toddler, said, no, I got it.

16:17.324 --> 16:18.545
And we stiff-arm God.

16:18.585 --> 16:20.989
We do that in our lives over and over again.

16:21.269 --> 16:22.671
I am so guilty of this.

16:23.012 --> 16:24.754
I see it in my kids, and I'm like,

16:24.898 --> 16:26.663
You don't know how to tie your shoes.

16:26.703 --> 16:27.445
You don't got it.

16:28.368 --> 16:30.534
But they are stubborn and persistent.

16:30.896 --> 16:33.644
And then I realized that I do the very same thing.

16:33.824 --> 16:35.108
No, God, I got this.

16:35.188 --> 16:37.234
And we create this separation.

16:37.506 --> 16:56.855
but God and God's generosity gives of God's self so that we might be brought back so that what we lost in the garden might be restored and we might have a relationship with the God who engages, who cares, who loves us enough to give generously of God's very self to us and for us.

16:58.858 --> 17:01.682
The relationship between a parent and a child

17:01.890 --> 17:04.817
is one of the most personal of all relationships.

17:05.178 --> 17:15.704
Jesus exemplified that when he cried out and he prayed, Abba, Father, revealing the intimate status that they shared, the love that was between them.

17:15.744 --> 17:19.794
And Jesus' status as a son and an heir.

17:20.514 --> 17:23.898
And the Father transmitted that love to the Son.

17:24.218 --> 17:28.663
And the Son then transmits that love to all Christ followers.

17:28.723 --> 17:43.220
And then as Christ followers, we are called to transmit that same parental love into the world around us, to grow the community of Christ one life at a time, to nurture our families and to grow this family of faith.

17:44.802 --> 17:48.626
So while we have examined the parental nature of God, this

17:49.186 --> 17:52.131
pattern of God's love and grace for us.

17:52.692 --> 17:59.764
The application of that is for all of us, anyone who nurtures and leads.

17:59.964 --> 18:10.322
Whether you are single, whether you are married, a social worker, a mentor, a teacher who cares about their kids, parents, leaders, bosses, this is for all of us.

18:10.626 --> 18:15.752
As Christ followers, we are called to be ambassadors of this parental love in the world.

18:16.133 --> 18:21.279
We are called to represent and promote God's love in the world.

18:21.920 --> 18:30.671
And this model of parental love that is revealed in Jesus gives us a pattern for living and engaging in relationship with God and with others.

18:31.452 --> 18:36.898
This life is built on small gestures that are repeated daily, over and over again.

18:36.919 --> 18:39.762
And fearless moment we call this rinse and repeat.

18:39.938 --> 18:42.421
and rinse and repeat over and over again.

18:42.461 --> 18:44.724
But that is the nature of the kingdom of God.

18:45.445 --> 18:56.238
The kingdom of God is like the yeast that the woman puts into the dough and it leavens the entire loaf of bread, the bread that nourishes her body and the bodies of her family.

18:57.499 --> 19:09.394
The kingdom of God is like the tiny mustard seed that is planted and grows into a great tree that becomes a home, a place of belonging, a place of hospitality for all of the birds of the air to nest.

19:09.986 --> 19:12.031
that is the nature of God.

19:12.432 --> 19:14.035
It is nurturing and hospitable.

19:14.076 --> 19:22.976
And if we follow this pattern of parental love, we can create this environment by, first of all, being self-expanding.

19:23.037 --> 19:25.362
Now, I

19:25.730 --> 19:26.972
My parents are so awesome.

19:26.992 --> 19:29.557
I'm so grateful for the family that I grew up with.

19:29.657 --> 19:33.324
I saw over and over again how much they gave of themselves for me.

19:33.805 --> 19:35.408
Actually, they continue to do that.

19:35.468 --> 19:40.217
I saw my parents yesterday and my dad helped me wash my car and my mom was like, here, you should borrow this shirt.

19:40.517 --> 19:42.962
They are always giving of themselves.

19:43.298 --> 19:51.032
And it was evident that they, how much they sacrificed to create this place of belonging, this nurturing and comforting place for my siblings and I.

19:51.393 --> 19:59.127
But it wasn't until I became a parent myself that I realized exactly how much, well, may, probably tried to imagine how much.

19:59.188 --> 20:00.530
I can never really know.

20:00.610 --> 20:16.597
And we can never really know how much God cares about us, but we have this tiny glimpse, these relationships that God gives us that are tiny glimpses into how much God cares for us, how much God gave of God's very self for us.

20:17.899 --> 20:21.746
Now, I was looking up, expand in the thesaurus,

20:21.922 --> 20:26.427
One, because I had a really great fourth grade writing teacher, shout out to Ms. Brooks.

20:26.928 --> 20:30.933
And second, because Word kept trying to expand, to expand.

20:31.454 --> 20:34.337
And I'm really trying not to be self-expanding at the moment.

20:34.377 --> 20:44.610
And my favorite synonym that I came across when I was looking through this list and the source was to throw around like confetti.

20:45.611 --> 20:51.538
Now, self-expending can sound exhausting, especially when we're doing it on our own accord.

20:52.034 --> 20:53.436
We're doing it by ourselves.

20:53.456 --> 20:58.323
We give and we give and we give and then we wonder what happens when there's nothing left.

20:59.164 --> 21:07.897
But when we give out of what we have been given, out of the life and the love that God has given us, that is when we can throw it around like confetti.

21:07.917 --> 21:11.061
And that is when things start to get fun and exciting.

21:11.362 --> 21:14.386
What if we live our lives that

21:14.978 --> 21:19.363
revealed the generosity of God, that reflected God's goodness in the world.

21:19.744 --> 21:26.112
What if we gave of others like God gave us Jesus, like God gave us hope, like God gave us new life?

21:26.512 --> 21:29.716
And now I feel like Oprah, you get a car, you get a car, you get a car.

21:29.756 --> 21:33.320
And instead of being exhausting, that's very empowering.

21:34.282 --> 21:35.463
This is when it gets fun.

21:35.503 --> 21:39.848
When we throw God's goodness and God's parental love around like confetti.

21:40.129 --> 21:44.434
When we throw God's grace around like confetti, even on our drive to work.

21:44.706 --> 21:48.936
when we throw God's love and goodness and patience around like confetti.

21:48.956 --> 21:55.894
That is when things get fun and exciting and start to sound like a party and everybody loves a party.

21:57.878 --> 22:01.447
Because of what we have been given in Christ, we can do that.

22:01.527 --> 22:02.610
We can throw

22:02.690 --> 22:05.534
God's love and God's goodness around like a confetti.

22:05.594 --> 22:09.158
We can freely give to others because of what we have been given.

22:09.459 --> 22:14.685
We can share our lives because we have been given new life, life to the full.

22:14.725 --> 22:17.669
And in this way, the party never ends.

22:20.072 --> 22:24.958
Our pattern of parental love is also communicated to others as we are other upholding.

22:26.040 --> 22:31.186
Philippians 2.4 says, let each of you look not to your own interests,

22:31.266 --> 22:33.008
but to the interests of others.

22:33.729 --> 22:39.536
Paul is painting a picture here of mutual care that reflects the care that God has for us.

22:40.036 --> 22:44.281
The next verse says, what you're added to be the same as that of Christ Jesus.

22:44.662 --> 22:50.509
So when we care for our children, we are helping them to grow and to become the people that God has called them to be.

22:50.769 --> 22:54.133
But this isn't just limited to a parent and child relationship.

22:54.453 --> 22:56.716
The same applies to all of our relationships.

22:56.736 --> 22:58.578
When we care about others,

22:59.010 --> 23:05.419
When we uphold one another, we are helping one another become the people who God created us to be.

23:05.800 --> 23:08.984
It takes all of us to be the body of Christ.

23:09.285 --> 23:12.890
Now, this is the opposite of using others to satisfy our own needs.

23:13.270 --> 23:24.466
Rather, care is a process relating to others in a way that is mindful of their needs, mindful of their growth, of their potential, and their value as a child of God.

23:25.026 --> 23:34.498
In caring for others, we point beyond ourselves to a greater reality, to a God whose parent who loves and cares for us eternally.

23:35.940 --> 23:43.850
Now there's a story in Exodus chapter 17 where Moses is leading God's people and they are attacked by the Amalekite army.

23:44.471 --> 23:48.236
God tells Moses to go up to the hill and to hold up his staff.

23:48.797 --> 23:53.042
And as long as Moses is holding up his staff, holding up his arms,

23:53.346 --> 23:54.791
Israel is winning the battle.

23:55.072 --> 23:58.565
To any time his arms drop down the Amalekites take new land.

23:58.626 --> 24:00.914
Now Moses is friends.

24:01.346 --> 24:08.154
His brother, Aaron, and friend, her, H-U-R, not H-E-R, though Moses was surrounded by a lot of really strong women.

24:08.434 --> 24:11.477
But in this case, her and Aaron saw a knee.

24:11.537 --> 24:18.044
They saw a place where they could step in and help, where they could be used by God for everyone's benefit.

24:18.565 --> 24:20.808
And they bring a stone for Moses to sit on.

24:21.068 --> 24:26.674
And they hold up his arms for the rest of the day until the battle is won.

24:27.522 --> 24:28.603
It took all of them.

24:28.663 --> 24:41.996
God used all of them as they considered each other's needs and what would be best for God's people to uphold one another, to build one another up to the people that God created them to be.

24:43.397 --> 24:49.243
Third, this pattern of parental love plays out as we are community building.

24:50.064 --> 24:56.690
Our vision is to grow the community of Christ one life at a time, to increase this family

24:56.770 --> 24:57.651
of faith.

24:58.572 --> 25:05.862
The widely known and well-dressed theologian, Harry Styles, says, you can start a family who will always show you love.

25:06.423 --> 25:08.105
And that is what we are trying to do here.

25:08.606 --> 25:09.567
We are not perfect.

25:09.787 --> 25:23.986
We do not always perfectly communicate God's love, but our hearts beat for others to know that perfect love, to join this family of faith so that they might know God's grace and God's goodness.

25:25.186 --> 25:31.794
If you haven't been out to the community first village that's run by mobile elves and fishes, you have got to go out there.

25:32.134 --> 25:36.199
If you're not familiar with mobile elves and fishes, you can contact Natalie Rolf.

25:36.219 --> 25:38.082
She's on staff, or you can scan your QR card.

25:39.223 --> 25:47.213
Mobile elves and fishes is a ministry where we serve the under-resourced, and those who are experiencing homelessness, we bring them food and clothes.

25:47.513 --> 25:54.802
They also have a branch where they have a neighborhood, where they are literally lifting people up off of the streets.

25:54.882 --> 26:05.195
plugging them in to a community, to a family, a place where they can belong, where they can thrive, where they can regain the things that were lost.

26:05.576 --> 26:12.765
And one beautiful thing about this community is that all of the houses have front facing, have porches that face one another.

26:13.346 --> 26:16.530
And so everyone knows their neighbors.

26:17.122 --> 26:20.109
They see when their people are coming and going.

26:20.129 --> 26:22.374
They notice when there is a need.

26:22.434 --> 26:23.737
They check on each other.

26:23.798 --> 26:25.241
They care about each other.

26:26.564 --> 26:29.310
I recently learned that this model is nothing new.

26:29.411 --> 26:35.986
In fact, this model for living in community and family existed in the time of Christ.

26:36.290 --> 26:40.736
buildings, these clusters of buildings where families lived together were called insulas.

26:41.117 --> 26:51.952
They were created around a central courtyard where aunts and uncles and cousins and grandparents all lived together and served each other, cared for each other on a daily basis.

26:53.474 --> 26:59.322
Now, these insulas also continued to grow as the family would grow.

26:59.983 --> 27:04.850
As the son found a wife, the father would oversee the son

27:04.930 --> 27:08.574
Building on, building a room on to this insulin.

27:08.594 --> 27:17.784
And the father would watch because it was the father who knew what it took to build and to keep a home, to cultivate community and to nurture a family.

27:17.804 --> 27:21.427
And the father would tell the son, okay, now the room is ready.

27:21.988 --> 27:31.538
And at this point, the excited groom would go and get his wife and bring her to her new home, to her new family, to her new community.

27:32.034 --> 27:40.230
Jesus used this image of the insula, these buildings that existed, connected, where families loved each other and lived together.

27:40.270 --> 27:45.941
When he said, in my father's house, there are many rooms, and I am going there to prepare a place for you.

27:47.564 --> 27:48.786
Jesus is

27:49.378 --> 27:58.994
He uses this word picture to present himself as the bride groom, who would go and bring us as Christ followers into the house of God, into the family of faith.

27:59.014 --> 28:03.601
And by using this familiar imagery of the insula, he helps Jesus as followers.

28:03.942 --> 28:16.082
He helps us to understand the kingdom of God as a household of faith, as a place where God's family lives in close, tight-knit community, where it grows, where we build on

28:16.482 --> 28:18.304
to the point that the limit does not exist.

28:18.484 --> 28:22.649
How many rooms this insula, this house of God could have.

28:23.290 --> 28:26.073
This stands in stark contrast to our individualistic society.

28:26.393 --> 28:28.195
This is a model that is attractive.

28:28.535 --> 28:34.562
When people see this and they notice and they want to be apart, we have room to invite them in.

28:36.004 --> 28:38.286
We cannot do these three things alone.

28:38.707 --> 28:41.610
We cannot do them apart from God's grace.

28:42.171 --> 28:45.074
We must first understand that Jesus

28:45.570 --> 28:48.675
has given us, has very soft.

28:49.016 --> 28:53.523
He died and he rose again on the cross to forgive us of our sins.

28:54.625 --> 28:59.092
And when we encounter this sort of grace, it transforms us.

28:59.653 --> 29:04.000
It changes the way that we engage with God and with one another.

29:04.642 --> 29:07.346
God has this grace for us today.

29:07.458 --> 29:13.104
Not grace enough to cover just your past mistakes or grace that waits for you in heaven one day.

29:13.164 --> 29:16.807
No, God has grace for us today in this very moment.

29:16.968 --> 29:19.590
Grace that meets you right where you are.

29:20.091 --> 29:32.844
Grace that covers your darkest parenting moment, that covers your loneliness, your regret, your inability, your pride, whatever you are carrying today, God's grace is sufficient for that.

29:34.385 --> 29:35.346
Would you bow your heads?

29:37.506 --> 29:44.073
God gives us this grace, but God also gives us a choice and responding to this parental love.

29:45.654 --> 29:49.538
We have the freedom to accept or reject this love.

29:50.699 --> 29:59.228
Luke 13 says, how often I have longed to gather your children together as a hen gathers her brood under her wings, but you were not willing.

30:00.609 --> 30:05.234
Here, God gives us a picture of a father who longs to give care

30:05.378 --> 30:10.285
to give and receive affection, but gives us the freedom to choose.

30:12.608 --> 30:15.592
That love and grace is available for us today.

30:15.652 --> 30:17.114
It is ours for the taking.

30:17.374 --> 30:23.563
So whatever you're walking for, you in this moment can exchange that burden for God's grace.

30:24.364 --> 30:34.578
And if you haven't yet stepped into a relationship, if you haven't made that choice, you wanna give you the opportunity to do that for the first time, right where you're sitting silently,

30:35.106 --> 30:37.629
If you say a prayer, that sounds something like this.

30:38.751 --> 30:39.612
God, we need you.

30:39.652 --> 30:41.615
We cannot do this apart from you.

30:42.916 --> 30:44.358
God, we need your grace.

30:45.500 --> 30:49.505
We accept your gift of grace, forgiveness in our lives.

30:51.127 --> 30:55.613
God, we choose to follow you with all that we have.

30:56.254 --> 30:57.956
We accept this parental love.

30:57.976 --> 31:02.322
We ask that you would transform our lives, that you

31:03.714 --> 31:06.820
would make me the person that you have created me to be.

31:07.321 --> 31:08.463
God, I love you.

31:09.284 --> 31:10.927
I'm grateful for your forgiveness.

31:11.368 --> 31:12.430
I choose to follow you.

31:15.836 --> 31:17.099
With everyone's heads still bowed.

31:17.139 --> 31:21.807
If you prayed that prayer this morning, we as a family are so excited for you.

31:22.148 --> 31:24.312
This is the best decision that you have ever made.

31:24.352 --> 31:26.095
We want to walk alongside of you.

31:26.256 --> 31:27.538
We want to celebrate

31:27.618 --> 31:31.003
with you, we want to help take your next steps with you.

31:31.284 --> 31:39.818
We also want to help you mark this moment, the moment that you stepped into relationship with God, where you joined this family, where you adopted into God's family of faith.

31:39.838 --> 31:44.606
And you can do that by raising your hand right where you are, just marking this moment.

31:47.430 --> 31:54.802
And we have our tradition around here that as you put your hands down, we put our hands together and tell you, welcome home.

